      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Open the clams",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Put {{clams}} of scrubbed clams in a large pot with {{white-wine-dry}} of white wine. Cover tightly and cook over high heat for 3 to 4 minutes, shaking once, until the clams have opened. Discard any that remain closed. Strain the liquid through a fine sieve lined with kitchen paper; you should have about 400 ml of clam liquor. Pick the clam meat from the shells and set aside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the chowder base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "In the same pot over medium heat, cook {{streaky-bacon}} of bacon lardons until the fat renders and the bacon is crisp, about 5 minutes. Add {{unsalted-butter}} of butter; melt. Add {{onion}} diced onion and {{celery}} diced celery; cook for 8 minutes until soft. Add {{plain-flour}} of flour and stir for 2 minutes. Gradually add the strained clam liquor and {{whole-milk}} of milk, whisking until smooth. Add {{potato}} of diced potato, {{bay-leaves}} of bay leaves and {{thyme}} of thyme. Simmer for 15 minutes until the potato is tender.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Finish and serve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Remove the bay leaves and thyme. Stir in {{double-cream}} of double cream and the reserved clam meat. Heat gently for 2 minutes without boiling. Season carefully with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt and {{white-pepper}} of white pepper; the clam liquor is already salty. Ladle into bowls.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add the clam meat only at the final stage, after the cream, and heat very gently. Clams become rubbery after prolonged cooking.",
              "cause": "Clams added too early or reheated for too long.",
              "symptom": "Clam meat rubbery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Strain the liquor carefully through lined sieve and taste before seasoning. The briny clam liquid adds significant salt.",
              "cause": "Clam liquor not strained, or over-seasoned without tasting.",
              "symptom": "Soup too salty"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add more milk to loosen. A small amount of potato breaking down is desirable and natural; if they dissolve entirely, remove half and mash roughly before returning.",
              "cause": "Too much roux, or potatoes breaking down completely.",
              "symptom": "Soup too thick"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "New England clam chowder is a coastal dish with a long history: a hearty soup made from the most abundant ingredient along the Massachusetts shore. Boston and Providence both claim a version. The Manhattan chowder, made with tomato instead of cream, is the New York version and the subject of strong opinions. This version makes no apologies for the cream.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
